{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> φρίσσω</b>, <br /> <i>Attic dialect</i> <b>φρίττω</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 387c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>future</i> φρίξω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 13.365 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]: <i>aorist</i> ἔφριξα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 13.339, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> πέφρῑκα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 11.383, etc.\">Refs</a>]; <i>poetry</i> <i>participle</i> πεφρίκοντες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.183 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>pluperfect</i> ἐπεφρίκει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.781e, 4th c.AD: Alciphro Epistolographus 1.1:\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>] —<i>middle</i>, <i>aorist 1</i> ἐφριξάμην <i>falsa lectio</i> in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Polyaenus Historicus 4.6.7. [ῑ by nature, hence to be accented φρῖσσον in 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 171, φρῖξαι 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 1408 (Lyric poetry)]\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>to be rough</b> or <b>uneven on the surface, bristle,</b> φρίσσουσιν ἄρουραι (i.e. σταχύεσσι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.599; φρίξας κάρπιμος στάχυς 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Supplices” 31 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of a line of battle, ἔφριξεν μάχη ἐγχείῃσιν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 13.339; φάλαγγες σάκεσίν τε καὶ ἔγχεσι πεφρικυῖαι 4.282, compare 7.62 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; φρίξας εὐλόφῳ σφηκώματι, of the crest of a helmet, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 341 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of a tree, φρίσσουσα ζεφύροις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Eleg.” 25; φιάλα χρυσῷ πεφρικυῖα 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “I.” 6(5).40 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χερσὶ δεξιωνύμοις ἔφριξεν αἰθήρ, of a crowd holding up their hands to vote, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 608 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; of hair, mane, or bristles, <b>bristle up, stand on end,</b> μηδ᾽ ὀρθαὶ φρίσσωσιν [τρίχες] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 540, compare 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 560b8, “Pr.” 888a38; ἔφριξαν ἔθειραι 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 25.244 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of foliage, φύλλα πεφρικότα, opposed to κεκλιμένα, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 3.9.4: with _accusative_ of respect, φρίξας εὖ λοφιήν\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] <b>having set up his bristly</b> mane, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 19.446; φ. τρίχας 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 391 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; φ. νῶτον, αὐχένας, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 13.473, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 171; χαίταν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 822 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; also πτεροῖσι νῶτα πεφρίκοντες <b>bristling on</b> their backs with feathers, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.183; λέοντος δέρος χαίτῃ πεφρικός 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 1121. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> ἄσθματι φρίσσων πνοάς <b>ruckling</b> in his throat, of one just dying, uncertain reading in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 10.74. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> of the <b>rippling</b> surface of smooth water [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare (φρίξ 1), φ. θάλασσαι.. πνοιῇσι 2nd c.AD: Dionysius Periegeta 112, compare 4th c.AD: Alciphro Epistolographus 1.1 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; of breakers, ῥηγμῖνες φ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 4.1575, compare 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “De Natura Animalium - Ar.Byzantine Epit.” 7.33 \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; also of rain, φρίσσοντες ὄμβροι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.81, explained by Scholia as φρίσσειν ποιοῦντες,compare ὁπόταν.. φρίσσων Βορέας ἐπισπέρχῃ [prev. author] “Parth.” 2.18. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> frequently of a feeling of <b>chill, shiver, shudder</b>: <br /><Level3><b>__II.1</b></Level3> of the effect of cold, <b>shiver,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 512, 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ παθῶν” 11, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Problemata” 963a33, 965a33 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; χωρὶς τοῦ φρῖξαι unless he <b>catch a chill,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 10.803\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; of the teeth, <b>chatter,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis “Ars Rhetorica” 10.9. \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> of the effect of fear, <b>shudder,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 1408 (Lyric poetry), “Tr.” 1044; πέφρικ᾽ ἐγὼ μέν, αὖός εἰμι τῷ δέει 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus “Ἐπιτρέποντες” 480; φ. γαῖα πόντος τε “Hymni Homerici” 27.8 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἅλω δὲ πολλὴν.. ἔφριζα δινήσαντος I <b>shuddered</b> when he swung the vast shield round, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 490 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; οὐ φρίττουσιν (i.e. animals) ὡς φρίττουσιν οἱ ἄνθρωποι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “D.” 1.12 \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]: with <i>accusative</i>, <b>shudder at</b> one, οἵ τέ σε πεφρίκασι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.383; πάντες δέ με πεφρίκασιν 24.775, compare 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 7.38, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 997, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 1133; τῶν δημοτέων φ. τὸν ἥκιστον 3rd c.BC: Herodas Mimographus 2.30; τοὺς τελώνας πᾶσα νῦν θύρη φρίσσει [prev. author] 6.64; πεφρικέναι τὸν θάνατον 1st c.BC: Philodemus Philosophus “de Morte - Papiri Ercolanesi” 39; φρίττουσι τὴν σύντροφόν τε καὶ φίλην οἱ ἰχθύες θάλατταν 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “De Natura Animalium - Ar.Byzantine Epit.” 9.57: with _accusative_ et \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>infinitive</i>, πέφρικα.. Ἐρινὺν τελέσαι I <b>tremble</b> at the thought of her accomplishing.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 720 (Lyric poetry) (but not with _dative_, for ἐρετμοῖσι φρίξουσι\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] they <b>shall shudder</b> at the oars is <i>falsa lectio</i> for{φρύξουσι} in Oracle texts cited in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.96): with \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>participle</i>, πέφρικα λεύσσων I <b>shudder at</b> seeing, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 346; φ. σε δερκομένα [prev. author] “Pr.” 540 (Lyric poetry), compare 695 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>infinitive</i>, <b>fear to</b> do, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.135: with _preposition_, φ. πρὸς τοὺς πόνους 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.8f; φ. πρὸς τὴν ἀκοὴν τῆς Ῥωμαίων τέχνης 4th c.AD: Libanius Sophista “Orationes” 24.16; φ. ὑπὲρ ὧν προσήκει παθεῖν 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 51.9. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> <b>feel a holy thrill</b> or <b>awe at,</b> ἐν ἱερῷ φ. ἅπαντα καὶ προσκυνεῖν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.26b; τοὺς θεοὺς πέφρικα 4th c.AD: Julianus Imperator “Orationes” 7.212b, +others \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.4</b></Level3> <b>thrill</b> with passionate joy, ἔφριξ᾽ ἔρωτι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 693, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 387 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>].—Rare in early Prose, except in the sense of <b>shuddering, fearing,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 387c, “Phdr.” 251a, D.[same places] \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5425","accentedUnicode":"φρίσσω","shortDef":"to shudder","mediumDef":"to shudder <br /><b>to be ruffled, to bristle; to shiver, shudder</b>, from fear, <ref='Jas.2.19'>Jas. 2:19</ref>*","stepGloss":"to shudder","stepTransliteration":"frissō","count":1,"_es_Definition":"temblar con temor","_zh_tw_Definition":"(因恐懼) 顫抖 (雅 2:19)","_zh_Definition":"(因恐惧) 颤抖 (雅 2:19)","_step_Type":"verb","_vi_Definition":"run sợ; sởn gáy; rung rinh, lo sợ","_zh_tw_Gloss":"戰驚","_es_Gloss":"temblar","_zh_Gloss":"战惊"}]}